{{Infobox Hieroglyphen
|NAME = <hiero>F22-G43-Z1*Z1 U28-M17-M17-t N14-N33:N33:N33</hiero> 
|NAME-TRANSKRIPTION = Pehui-djat<br/>''Pḥ.wj-ḏ3j.t''
|NAME-ERKLÄRUNG = Pehui-djat
}}

'''Pehui-djat''' is the designation of an {{ill|Ancient Egypt|de|Altes Ägypten|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} {{ill|Decade (Ancient Egypt)|de|Dekade (Altägypten)|1=Decan|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, which comprised three {{ill|Baktiu|de|Baktiu|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} (decan stars).

Since all associated {{ill|Celestial object|de|Himmelsobjekt|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}s are very faint, no {{ill|Star|de|Stern|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} stands out as particularly prominent. The decan stars can be localized within the regions of the constellations {{ill|Hydra (constellation)|de|Wasserschlange (Sternbild)|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Vela (constellation)|de|Segel des Schiffs|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}.

In the decan lists of the {{ill|Book of Nut#Pharaonic period|lt=Pharaonic period|de|Nutbuch#Pharaonische Zeit|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, Pehui-djat represented the fourth decan on the body of {{ill|Nut (Egyptian mythology)|de|Nut (Ägyptische Mythologie)|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}. The {{ill|Heliacal rising|de|Heliakisch|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} was set for the {{ill|Season of the Harvest|lt=Shemu#Dating|lt=6th Schemu II|de|6. Schemu II|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, based on the arrangement ordered under {{ill|Senusret III|de|Sesostris III.|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Twelfth Dynasty of Egypt|de|12. Dynastie|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}) in his seventh year of reign.

== Literature ==
* {{Interlanguage link|12=draft|Christian Leitz|fr|Christian Leitz|en|Christian Leitz|de|Christian Leitz}}: ''Altägyptische Sternuhren''. Peeters, Leuven 1995, ISBN 90-6831-669-9, p. 95.  
* {{ill|Alexandra von Lieven|fr|Alexandra von Lieven|de|Alexandra von Lieven|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}: ''Grundriss des Laufes der Sterne – Das sogenannte Nutbuch''. The Carsten Niebuhr Institute of Ancient Eastern Studies (et al.), Copenhagen 2007, ISBN 978-87-635-0406-5, pp. 62–67 and 385.







