Since all associated {{ill|Celestial object|de|Himmelsobjekt|qq=draft|qq=draft}}s are very faint, no {{ill|Star|de|Stern|qq=draft|qq=draft}} stands out as particularly prominent. The decan stars can be localized within the regions of the constellations {{ill|Hydra (constellation)|de|Wasserschlange (Sternbild)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Vela (constellation)|de|Segel des Schiffs|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

In the decan lists of the {{ill|Book of Nut#Pharaonic period|lt=Pharaonic period|de|Nutbuch#Pharaonische Zeit|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Pehui-djat represented the fourth decan on the body of {{ill|Nut (Egyptian mythology)|de|Nut (Ägyptische Mythologie)|1=Nut (goddess)|lt=Nut|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. The {{ill|Heliacal rising|de|Heliakisch|qq=draft|qq=draft}} was set for the {{ill|Season of the Harvest|lt=Shemu#Dating|lt=6th Schemu II|de|6. Schemu II|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, based on the arrangement ordered under {{ill|Senusret III|de|Sesostris III.|qq=draft|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Twelfth Dynasty of Egypt|de|12. Dynastie|qq=draft|qq=draft}}) in his seventh year of reign.

